{"title_page": "Jellaz Cemetery", "text_new": "{{Infobox cemetery\n| name         = Jellaz Cemetery'\n| native_name  = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image        = Djellaz1.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = '''Al-Jallaz cemetery'''; in the distance ''Sidi Belhassen Chadli''\n| map_type     = \n| map_size     = \n| map_caption  = \n| established  = \n| abandoned    = <!-- or | closed = -->\n| location     = \n| country      = \n| coordinates  = \n| type         = \n| style        = \n| owner        = \n| size         = \n| graves       = \n| interments   = \n| cremations   = \n| leases       = \n| website      = \n| findagraveid = \n| politicalgeo = \n| footnotes    = \n| nrhp         = \n| embedded     = \n}}\n'''Jellaz Cemetery''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0645\u0642\u0628\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0644\u0627\u0632}} ''Maqbara al-Jal\u0101z''; also known as '''al-Jallaz''') is a large hillside Muslim cemetery in [[Tunis]], Tunisia, established in the thirteenth century. Located next to the bus station, the cemetery is the largest in the city. The [[Borj Ali Rais]] [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] fortress is visible from most places in the cemetery.<ref name=\"Jacobs and Morris\">{{cite book|authors=Jacobs, Daniel, Morris, Peter |edition=6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k2By-NdV93AC&pg=PP110&lpg=PP110&dq=Jellaz+Cemetery&source=bl&ots=ijx8blRCno&sig=-U8nW1DWjJAhxuYhk08ziaIvu-8&hl=en&ei=CrxOTJy3D4L74AbsyrTXBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CDAQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Jellaz%20Cemetery&f=false|title=Rough Guide to Tunisia|publisher=Rough Guide Travel Guides|page=94|year=2001|isbn=1-85828-748-0}}</ref> Visiting the cemetery is a duty during [[Aid el Fitr]] at the end of [[Ramadan]]. Family members at this time clean and paint the tombs, which face [[Mecca]].\n\nIn 1911, mass protests known as the [[Jellaz Affair]] demonstrations took place at the cemetery against the French, triggered by land registration and entitlement disputes. These in turn led to the [[Tunis Tram Boycott]],.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tunisianassociation.btik.com/news/21669149896.ikml |title=The Young Tunisians movement |publisher=Tunisia Association |accessdate=July 27, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> A bloody confrontation took place after the burial of the wife of an eager propagandist of naturalisation and resulted in the death of 39 people, nine of them French and five Italian.<ref name=\"Jacobs and Morris\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Tunisia|publisher=[[Eyewitness Guides]]|year=2008|page=87}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n*[[Chokri Belaid]], lawyer and politician\n*[[Moncef Bey]], former Bey of Tunisia under French Rule\n*[[Mohamed Brahmi]], politician, founder and former leader of the [[People's Movement (Tunisia)|People's Movement]]\n*[[Beji Caid Essebsi]], former [[president of Tunisia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/elmina/408197015/sizes/o/ Photograph]\n\n{{coord|36|47|10|N|10|11|04|E|type:landmark_source:kolossus-frwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Tunis]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:13th-century establishments in Africa]]\n\n\n{{Cemetery-stub}}\n{{Tunisia-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cemetery\n| name         = Jellaz Cemetery'\n| native_name  = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image        = Djellaz1.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = '''Al-Jallaz cemetery'''; in the distance ''Sidi Belhassen Chadli''\n| map_type     = \n| map_size     = \n| map_caption  = \n| established  = \n| abandoned    = <!-- or | closed = -->\n| location     = \n| country      = \n| coordinates  = \n| type         = \n| style        = \n| owner        = \n| size         = \n| graves       = \n| interments   = \n| cremations   = \n| leases       = \n| website      = \n| findagraveid = \n| politicalgeo = \n| footnotes    = \n| nrhp         = \n| embedded     = \n}}\n'''Jellaz Cemetery''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0645\u0642\u0628\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0644\u0627\u0632}} ''Maqbara al-J\u0101l\u0101z''; also known as '''al-Jallaz''') is a large hillside Muslim cemetery in [[Tunis]], Tunisia, established in the thirteenth century. Located next to the bus station, the cemetery is the largest in the city. The [[Borj Ali Rais]] [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] fortress is visible from most places in the cemetery.<ref name=\"Jacobs and Morris\">{{cite book|authors=Jacobs, Daniel, Morris, Peter |edition=6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k2By-NdV93AC&pg=PP110&lpg=PP110&dq=Jellaz+Cemetery&source=bl&ots=ijx8blRCno&sig=-U8nW1DWjJAhxuYhk08ziaIvu-8&hl=en&ei=CrxOTJy3D4L74AbsyrTXBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CDAQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=Jellaz%20Cemetery&f=false|title=Rough Guide to Tunisia|publisher=Rough Guide Travel Guides|page=94|year=2001|isbn=1-85828-748-0}}</ref> Visiting the cemetery is a duty during [[Aid el Fitr]] at the end of [[Ramadan]]. Family members at this time clean and paint the tombs, which face [[Mecca]].\n\nIn 1911, mass protests known as the [[Jellaz Affair]] demonstrations took place at the cemetery against the French, triggered by land registration and entitlement disputes. These in turn led to the [[Tunis Tram Boycott]],.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tunisianassociation.btik.com/news/21669149896.ikml |title=The Young Tunisians movement |publisher=Tunisia Association |accessdate=July 27, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> A bloody confrontation took place after the burial of the wife of an eager propagandist of naturalisation and resulted in the death of 39 people, nine of them French and five Italian.<ref name=\"Jacobs and Morris\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Tunisia|publisher=[[Eyewitness Guides]]|year=2008|page=87}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n*[[Chokri Belaid]], lawyer and politician\n*[[Moncef Bey]], former Bey of Tunisia under French Rule\n