{"title_page": "Ternovoye, Starooskolsky District, Belgorod Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Ternovoye\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0422\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435\n|native_name_lang       = ru\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Selo\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|pushpin_map            = Russia Belgorod Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Belgorod Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Starooskolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      =\n| population_as_of      = \n| population_footnotes  = \n| population_total      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          =\n|utc_offset1_DST        =\n|postal_code_type       =\n|postal_code            =\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_footnotes    =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|51|10|N|38|07|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/belgorodskaya-oblast/starooskolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Ternovoye''' ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|selo]]) in [[Starooskolsky District]], [[Belgorod Oblast]], Russia. The population was 188 as of 2010.<ref>[http://belg.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/belg/resources/eab54e804ff0fbbca305efd8c740ec4f/pub-01-15.pdf \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. 15. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0432]</ref> There are 5 streets.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Starooskolsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Belgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Starooskolsky District]]\n\n{{BelgorodOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Ternovoye\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0422\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435\n|native_name_lang       = ru\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Selo\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|pushpin_map            = Russia Belgorod Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Belgorod Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Starooskolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      =\n| population_as_of      = \n| population_footnotes  = \n| population_total      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          =\n|utc_offset1_DST        =\n|postal_code_type       =\n|postal_code            =\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_footnotes    =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|51|10|N|38|07|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/belgorodskaya-oblast/starooskolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Ternovoye''' ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u0435\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|selo]]) in [[Starooskolsky District]], [[Belgorod Oblast]], Russia. The population was 188 as of 2010.<ref>[http://belg.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/belg/resources/eab54e804ff0fbbca305efd8c740ec4f/pub-01-15.pdf \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. 15. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0432]</ref> There are 5 streets.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Starooskolsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Belgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Starooskolsky District]]\n\n\n{{BelgorodOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ternovoye,_Starooskolsky_District,_Belgorod_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Mro people (Awa Khami)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Mro people (Mru)}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Khwemyi\n| native_name      = {{nobold|[[:my:%E1%80%99%E1%80%BC%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%9C%E1%80%B0%E1%80%99%E1%80%BB%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%B8\\ \u1001\u1019\u102d\u103c\u101c\u1030\u1019\u103a\u102d\u1033\u1038]]}}\n| native_name_lang = my\n| image            = Khwemyi Woman.jpg\n| image_caption    = Khwemyi Woman.jpg\n| total            = 77,527\u201383,000\n| total_year       = 2004\n| total_source     = estimate\n| total_ref        =\n| regions          = [[Myanmar]] ([[Chin State]], [[Rakhine State]]) \n| region1          = {{flag|Myanmar}}\n| pop1             = 83,000\n| languages        = [[Mro language|Mro]] (dialects: Arang (Ahraing Khami, Areung, Aroeng), Xengna (Hrengna, Xata, Vakung (Wakun, Wakung))\n| religions        = [[Animism]], [[Buddhism]] and [[Christianity]]\n| related_groups   = [[Chin people]]\n| footnotes        =\n\n}}\nThe '''Khwemyi''' or ''' Chin People'''  ({{lang-my| [[:my:%https://pyithu.hluttaw.mm/question-1020E1%80%99%E1%80%BC%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%9C%E1%80%B0%E1%80%99%E1%80%BB%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%B8|\u1001\u1019\u102d\u103c\u101c\u1030\u1019\u103a\u102d\u1033\u1038]]}}) also known as '''khami''', ''' (Wakim)''', '''Awa Khami''', '''Khami''', '''Khumi Awa''', '''Mro-Khimi''', or '''Kwe Myi''', are one of the 135 ethnic groups recognized by the government of [[Myanmar]]. They are identified as a sub-group of Chin people. They live widely in some parts of northern Rakine state, Chin state, the townships of Matupi and Paletwa, and the regions of Samechaung and Michaung. They are Tibeto-Burman and have their own language, culture and customs which are still in existence. For Chin specifically, the Awa Khami are one of 53 sub-groups identified by the government of Myanmar.\n\n== Religion ==\n\n=== Animism ===\nThe Mro People still believe animism as their custome, especially for their traditional festival. Merely 36.60%.\n\n=== Buddhism ===\nThe Mro practise both animism and Buddhism. A strong Buddhist influence exists as about 55% of the population adhering to Theravada Buddhism, a common sect of Buddhism eminent throughout mainland Southeast Asia, especially in Myanmar (Burma) and Thailand.\n\n=== Christianity ===\nMerely 7.14% of the Mro adheres to Christianity. New Testament was translated into Mro language in 2017.\n\n==Language==\n\nThey primarily speak the [[Mro(Mru) language]], a [[Kuki-Chin languages|Kuki-Chin language]]. Mro is spoken in the following townships of Myanmar (''[[Ethnologue]]'').\n*[[Chin State]]: [[Paletwa]] township\n*[[Rakhine State]]: [[Kyauktaw]], [[Buthidaung]], [[Ponnagyun]], [[Pauktaw]], [[Mrauk U]], and [[Maungdaw]] townships.\n\nThere are 4 main dialects of Mro (''[[Ethnologue]]'').\n\n*Arang (Ahraing Khami, Areung, Aroeng)\n*Xengna (Hrengna)\n*Xata\n*Vakung (Wakun, Wakung)\n\nArang (Ahraing Khami, Areung, Aroeng), Xengna (Hrengna), Xata, Vakung (Wakun, Wakung). Generally high comprehension of Vakung dialect among other dialect speakers. Wakun (Vakung) is the most widely spoken and understood dialect (Horney 2009:5) and basis of literature. Lexical similarity: 91%\u201398% within Mro(Khimi) varieties, 86%\u201390% with Likhy variety of Eastern Khumi [cek], 81%\u201385% with Lemi variety of Eastern Khumi [cek], 77%\u201381% with Kaladan Khumi [cnk].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Horn\u00e9y, Christina Scotte. 2012. ''A phonological analysis of Mro Khimi''. MA thesis, University of North Dakota.\n\n{{Languages of Burma}}\n{{Naga languages}}\n\n*[http://www.myanmar.gov.mm/ministry/hotel/fact/race.htm list of ethnic groups in Myanmar]\n*[http://nagarealm.com/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=6040 essay on the Chin peoples]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Burma}}\n\n[[Category:Kukish languages]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Myanmar]]\n\n\n{{st-lang-stub}}\n{{Myanmar-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Mru people (Mrucha)}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Mro\n| native_name      = {{nobold|[[:my:%E1%80%99%E1%80%BC%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%9C%E1%80%B0%E1%80%99%E1%80%BB%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%B8|\u1019\u103c\u102d\u102f\u101c\u1030\u1019\u103b\u102d\u102f\u1038]]}}\n| native_name_lang = my\n| image            = Mro Woman.jpg\n| image_caption    = Mro Woman.jpg\n| total            = 77,527\u201383,000\n| total_year       = 2004\n| total_source     = estimate\n| total_ref        =\n| regions          = [[Myanmar]] ([[Chin State]], [[Rakhine State]]) \n| region1          = {{flag|Myanmar}}\n| pop1             = 83,000\n| languages        = [[Mro language|Mro]] (dialects: Arang (Ahraing Khami, Areung, Aroeng), Xengna (Hrengna, Xata, Vakung (Wakun, Wakung))\n| religions        = [[Animism]], [[Buddhism]] and [[Christianity]]\n| related_groups   = [[Chin people]]\n| footnotes        =\n\n}}\nThe '''Mru''' or '''Mro Chin People'''  ({{lang-my| [[:my:%E1%80%99%E1%80%BC%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%9C%E1%80%B0%E1%80%99%E1%80%BB%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%B8|\u1019\u103c\u102d\u102f\u101c\u1030\u1019\u103b\u102d\u102f\u1038]]}}) also known as '''Mro''', '''Mro (Wakim)''', '''Awa Khami''', '''Khami''', '''Khumi Awa''', '''Mro-Khimi''', or '''Kwe Myi''', are one of the 135 ethnic groups recognized by the government of [[Myanmar]]. They are identified as a sub-group of Chin people. They live widely in some parts of northern Rakine state, Chin state, the townships of Matupi and Paletwa, and the regions of Samechaung and Michaung. They are Tibeto-Burman and have their own language, culture and customs which are still in existence. For Chin specifically, the Awa Khami are one of 53 sub-groups identified by the government of Myanmar.\n\n== Religion ==\n\n=== Animism ===\nThe Mro People still believe animism as their custome, especially for their traditional festival. Merely 36.60%.\n\n=== Buddhism ===\nThe Mro practise both animism and Buddhism. A strong Buddhist influence exists as about 55% of the population adhering to Theravada Buddhism, a common sect of Buddhism eminent throughout mainland Southeast Asia, especially in Myanmar (Burma) and Thailand.\n\n=== Christianity ===\nMerely 7.14% of the Mro adheres to Christianity. New Testament was translated into Mro language in 2017.\n\n==Language==\n\nThey primarily speak the [[Mro language]], a [[Kuki-Chin languages|Kuki-Chin language]]. Mro is spoken in the following townships of Myanmar (''[[Ethnologue]]'').\n*[[Chin State]]: [[Paletwa]] township\n*[[Rakhine State]]: [[Kyauktaw]], [[Buthidaung]], [[Ponnagyun]], [[Pauktaw]], [[Mrauk U]], and [[Maungdaw]] townships.\n\nThere are 4 main dialects of Mro (''[[Ethnologue]]'').\n\n*Arang (Ahraing Khami, Areung, Aroeng)\n*Xengna (Hrengna)\n*Xata\n*Vakung (Wakun, Wakung)\n\nArang (Ahraing Khami, Areung, Aroeng), Xengna (Hrengna), Xata, Vakung (Wakun, Wakung). Generally high comprehension of Vakung dialect among other dialect speakers. Wakun (Vakung) is the most widely spoken and understood dialect (Horney 2009:5) and basis of literature. Lexical similarity: 91%\u201398% within Mro(Khimi) varieties, 86%\u201390% with Likhy variety of Eastern Khumi [cek], 81%\u201385% with Lemi variety of Eastern Khumi [cek], 77%\u201381% with Kaladan Khumi [cnk].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Horn\u00e9y, Christina Scotte. 2012. ''A phonological analysis of Mro Khimi''. MA thesis, University of North Dakota.\n\n{{Languages of Burma}}\n{{Naga languages}}\n\n*[http://www.myanmar.gov.mm/ministry/hotel/fact/race.htm list of ethnic groups in Myanmar]\n*[http://nagarealm.com/index.php?name=News&file=article&sid=6040 essay on the Chin peoples]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Burma}}\n\n[[Category:Kukish languages]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Myanmar]]\n\n\n{{st-lang-stub}}\n{{Myanmar-stub}}\n", "name_user": "\u103b\u1019\u102d\u1033\u101c\u1030\u1019\u103a\u102d\u102f\u1038(\u1019\u101b\u1030)", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(redited)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mro_people_(Awa_Khami)"}
{"title_page": "Terekhovo, Starooskolsky District, Belgorod Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Terekhovo\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0422\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|native_name_lang       = ru\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Selo\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|pushpin_map            = Russia Belgorod Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Belgorod Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Starooskolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      =\n| population_as_of      = \n| population_footnotes  = \n| population_total      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          =\n|utc_offset1_DST        =\n|postal_code_type       =\n|postal_code            =\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_footnotes    =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|51|20|N|38|03|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/belgorodskaya-oblast/starooskolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Terekhovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|selo]]) in [[Starooskolsky District]], [[Belgorod Oblast]], Russia. The population was 434 as of 2010.<ref>[http://belg.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/belg/resources/eab54e804ff0fbbca305efd8c740ec4f/pub-01-15.pdf \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. 15. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0432]</ref> There are 15 streets.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Starooskolsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Belgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Starooskolsky District]]\n\n{{BelgorodOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Terekhovo\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = \u0422\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|native_name_lang       = ru\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Selo\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|pushpin_map            = Russia Belgorod Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Belgorod Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Starooskolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      =\n| population_as_of      = \n| population_footnotes  = \n| population_total      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          =\n|utc_offset1_DST        =\n|postal_code_type       =\n|postal_code            =\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_footnotes    =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|51|20|N|38|03|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/belgorodskaya-oblast/starooskolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Terekhovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0422\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|selo]]) in [[Starooskolsky District]], [[Belgorod Oblast]], Russia. The population was 434 as of 2010.<ref>[http://belg.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/belg/resources/eab54e804ff0fbbca305efd8c740ec4f/pub-01-15.pdf \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. 15. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0432]</ref> There are 15 streets.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Starooskolsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Belgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Starooskolsky District]]\n\n\n{{BelgorodOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terekhovo,_Starooskolsky_District,_Belgorod_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "2014 Clacton by-election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2014 Clacton by-election\n| type = parliamentary\n| country = United Kingdom\n| seats_for_election = [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]] constituency\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2010 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year = 2010\n| next_election = 2015 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year = 2015\n| election_date = 9 October 2014\n| candidate1 = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n| image1 =  [[File:Douglas Carswell.jpg|160x160px]]\n| party1 = UK Independence Party\n| last_election1 = \n| popular_vote1 = '''21,113'''\n| percentage1 = '''59.7%'''\n| swing1 = ''New party''\n| candidate2 = [[Giles Watling]]\n| image2 = [[File:Official portrait of Giles Watling crop 2.jpg|160x160px]]\n| party2 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| last_election2 =  \n| popular_vote2 = 8,709\n| percentage2 = 24.6%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}}28.4%\n| candidate3 = Tim Young\n| image3 = [[File:No image.svg|110px]]\n| party3 = Labour Party (UK)\n| last_election3 = \n| popular_vote3 = 3,957\n| percentage3 = 11.2%\n| swing3 = {{decrease}}13.8%\n| map_image = Clacton2007Constituency.svg\n| map_size = 150px\n| map_caption = Map showing the [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]] Parliamentary constituency within the [[England|English]] county of [[Essex]].\n| title = MP\n| posttitle = Subsequent MP\n| before_election = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n| before_party = Conservative Party (UK)\n| after_election = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n| after_party = UK Independence Party\n}}\n\nThe '''Clacton by-election''' was held on 9 October 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29029022 |title=Clacton by-election to be held on 9 October |publisher=BBC News |date=2 September 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> for the [[United Kingdom]] [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] of [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/update/2014-08-29/chancellor-makes-douglas-carswells-resignation-official/ |title=Chancellor makes Douglas Carswell's resignation official |publisher=Itv.com |date=29 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref><ref name = \"BBC_29_Aug\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28977961 |title=Stuart Wheeler: More Tory defections to UKIP 'odds on' |publisher=BBC News |date=29 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Swinford |first=Steven |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11060963/Douglas-Carswells-shock-defection-to-Ukip-triggers-by-election-battle.html |title=Douglas Carswell's shock defection to UKIP triggers by-election battle |publisher=Telegraph |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-08-29/carswell-and-farage-in-clacton-ahead-of-by-election/ |title=ITV News Carswell and Farage in Clacton Ahead of by-election |publisher=Itv.com |date=29 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> The by-election was triggered by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP for Clacton, [[Douglas Carswell]], defecting to the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) and subsequently [[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resigning]] his seat to seek re-election as its candidate.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nicholas |last=Watt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/28/douglas-carswell-ukip-defects-tory-mp-byelection |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell defects to Ukip and forces byelection |newspaper=The Guardian |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nStanding for UKIP, Carswell retained the seat with 59.7% of the vote, becoming UKIP's first elected MP. The Conservatives came second, and Labour third.  According to [[John Curtice]], professor of politics at [[Strathclyde University]], the result was the biggest increase in the share of a vote for any party in any by-election in history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b912186e-504f-11e4-8645-00144feab7de.html |title=Ukip surge sends tremors through Westminster |last1=Pickard |first1=Jim |last2=Odell |first2=Mark |date=10 October 2014 |work=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Douglas Carswell, May 2009.jpg|thumb|left|[[Douglas Carswell]] defected from the Conservatives to UKIP and triggered the by-election by resigning his seat]]\nOn 28 August 2014 Carswell, a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] backbencher, announced his defection to UKIP and said that he was resigning his seat in order to fight a by-election. He said he did not think Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] was \"serious about the change we need\", adding that \"many of those at the top of the Conservative Party are simply not on our side\" and \"Of course they talk the talk before elections. They say what they feel they must say to get our support when they want our support, but on so many issues \u2013 on modernising our politics, on the recall of MPs, on controlling our borders[,] on less government, on bank reform, on cutting public debt, on an EU referendum \u2013 they never actually make it happen\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28967904 |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell defects to UKIP and forces by-election |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=28 August 2014 |publisher=BBC News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422133403/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28967904 |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}.</ref> He also said: \"...local issues regarding planning and overcrowding of GP surgeries were a factor in my decision to resign\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11439315._Local_issues_affected_my_decision__claims_Carswell_following_defection_to_UKIP/?ref=var_0 |title=\"Local issues affected my decision\" claims Carswell following defection to UKIP |first=James |last=Dwan |date=28 August 2014 |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422185234/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11439315.local-issues-affected-my-decision-claims-carswell-following-defection-to-ukip/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nResponding to the news that Carswell had defected and would trigger a by-election, Cameron said the contest would be held \"as soon as possible\". He also confirmed that the Conservatives would contest the by-election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28967904 |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell defects to UKIP and forces by-election |publisher=BBC News |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> It was later announced that the by-election would be held on 9 October, which was also Cameron's 48th birthday. The poll was one of two parliamentary by-elections the same day, with [[2014 Heywood and Middleton by-election|an election]] also being held in the constituency of [[Heywood and Middleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Heywood and Middleton]] following the death of its MP, [[Jim Dobbin]] of Labour.<ref name=clacton>{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Joe|title=By-election battle: Fight for late MP Jim Dobbin's Heywood and Middleton seat begins before he is buried|url=http://www.mancunianmatters.co.uk/content/120970652-election-battle-fight-late-mp-jim-dobbins-heywood-and-middleton-seat-begins-he|work=Mancunian Matters|date=12 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnalysis of [[demographics]] for the constituency prior to the by-election were said to make it the most UKIP-friendly in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Osborn |first=Andrew|title=UKIP poised to snare first parliament seat in blow to Cameron |date=9 October 2014|work=The Independent|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/10/08/uk-britain-politics-idUKKCN0HX2H420141008|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Conservative reaction==\nThere was speculation that [[Boris Johnson]], the Conservative [[Mayor of London]], would seek the candidacy at the by-election. On 29 August 2014, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' journalist [[Peter Oborne]] wrote that: \"David Cameron should go down on his knees and beg Boris Johnson to stand as the Conservative Party's candidate for Clacton in the coming by-election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/peteroborne/100284436/why-david-cameron-must-beg-boris-johnson-to-fight-in-calcton/ |title=Why David Cameron must beg Boris Johnson to fight in Clacton |last=Oborne |first=Peter |date=29 August 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017021923/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/peteroborne/100284436/why-david-cameron-must-beg-boris-johnson-to-fight-in-calcton/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> The bookmaker [[Ladbrokes]] offered odds of 33-1 against Johnson standing in Clacton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/local-news/uxbridge-lose-boris-johnson-clacton-7690859 |title=Will Uxbridge lose Boris Johnson to Clacton seat? |last=Drewett |first=Zoe |date=29 August 2014 |publisher=MyLondon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422132843/https://www.mylondon.news/news/local-news/uxbridge-lose-boris-johnson-clacton-7690859 |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> He ruled out standing, saying that he was intent on fighting [[Uxbridge and South Ruislip (UK Parliament constituency)|Uxbridge and South Ruislip]] at the general election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/02/boris-johnson-clacton-carswell-ukip_n_5750712.html |title=Boris Johnson Rules Out Fighting Douglas Carswell For Clacton |last=Simons |first=Ned |date=2 September 2014 |work=Huffington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422133118/https://consent.yahoo.com/collectConsent?sessionId=2_cc-session_62807458-f846-47e6-be5b-7a2fed3c316e&lang=en-gb&inline=false |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile many Conservatives condemned Carswell's defection, some were more supportive of him. Conservative backbencher [[Nigel Evans]] suggested that possibly the Conservatives should not stand in Clacton.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nicholas |last=Watt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/31/tories-ukip-clacton-byelection-douglas-carswell?CMP=twt_gu |title=Tories should give Ukip free run in Clacton, MP suggests |newspaper=The Guardian |date=31 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> Former minister [[Norman Tebbit]] refused to campaign against Carswell and claimed that the \"House of Commons needs men like [[Douglas Carswell]]\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Norman |last=Tebbit |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/normantebbit/100284355/the-house-of-commons-needs-men-like-douglas-carswell-i-would-not-campaign-against-him/ |title=The House of Commons needs men like Douglas Carswell: I would not campaign against him |publisher=Blogs.telegraph.co.uk |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> Backbencher [[Zac Goldsmith]] described Carswell as a \"model Parliamentarian\" and remarked that \"I have nothing but admiration for him\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11060963/Douglas-Carswells-shock-defection-to-Ukip-triggers-by-election-battle.html |title=Douglas Carswell's shock defection to Ukip triggers by-election battle |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |last2=Holehouse |first2=Matthew |date=28 August 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422185747/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11060963/Douglas-Carswells-shock-defection-to-Ukip-triggers-by-election-battle.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Nick Herbert]], the former policing minister, said that the Conservative Party was more concerned with the Clacton by-election rather than winning the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]] that was held during the early part of the Clacton campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Swinford |first=Steven |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scottish-independence/11107017/Tory-MPs-expected-to-buy-ice-creams-in-Clacton-instead-of-going-to-Scotland.html |title=Tory MPs expected to 'buy ice-creams in Clacton' instead of going to Scotland |date=18 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422185942/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scottish-independence/11107017/Tory-MPs-expected-to-buy-ice-creams-in-Clacton-instead-of-going-to-Scotland.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\nDuring the campaign, a second Conservative MP and close friend of Carswell,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-29395030 |title=Conservative MP Mark Reckless defects to UKIP |publisher=BBC News |date=27 September 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> [[Mark Reckless]], likewise defected to UKIP and sought re-election in a [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|by-election]] for his constituency of [[Rochester and Strood (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochester and Strood]].\n\n==Candidates==\n[[Tendring District Council]], the local authority administering the by-election, confirmed the deadline for nominations as 4 pm on 16 September 2014.<ref>[http://www.tendringdc.gov.uk/council/elections-voting/clacton-constituency-parliamentary-election Clacton constituency parliamentary by-election] Tendring District Council</ref>\n\nCarswell announced that he would stand again for the seat as UKIP's candidate, although he was opposed by the recently selected UKIP candidate, Roger Lord,<ref>{{cite web|last=Holehouse |first=Matthew |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11065185/Douglas-Carswell-is-a-gutless-coward-says-ousted-UKIP-candidate-Roger-Lord.html |title='Douglas Carswell is a gutless coward' says ousted UKIP candidate Roger Lord |publisher=Telegraph |date=29 August 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> with some local activists speculating that they might not adopt Carswell. Anne Poonian, secretary of Clacton UKIP association, was quoted by [[Buzzfeed]] saying that, although she welcomed Carswell's decision to defect, he may not be selected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jimwaterson/ukips-clacton-candidate-says-he-wont-stand-down-for-douglas |title=UKIP's Clacton Candidate Says He Won't Stand Down For Douglas Carswell |last=Waterson |first=Jim |date=28 August 2014 |publisher=BuzzFeed News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423093530/https://www.buzzfeed.com/jimwaterson/ukips-clacton-candidate-says-he-wont-stand-down-for-douglas |url-status=live |archive-date=23 April 2020 |access-date=23 April 2020 |quote='Carswell's taking a very big risk for getting in for a little party. We may not adopt him as our candidate, who knows? He has to be adopted by us, the local association. At the moment he\u2019s just an unemployed MP. Who knows whether he\u2019ll be adopted?'}}</ref> However, UKIP rules for selecting by-election candidates invested the decision with the National Executive Committee, which selected Carswell.<ref name = \"BBC_29_Aug\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politicshome.com/uk/story/44030/ukip_candidate_blasts_stupid_carswell.html |title=Ukip candidate blasts 'stupid' Carswell |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 August 2014 |website=PoliticsHome |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903131533/http://www.politicshome.com/uk/story/44030/ukip_candidate_blasts_stupid_carswell.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 September 2014 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Lord left UKIP and resigned his County Council seat, supporting the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] in the council by-election.<ref name=\"EADT1\">[http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/essex_ukip_county_councillor_roger_lord_resigns_after_being_deselected_as_clacton_election_candidate_1_3755662 East Anglian Daily Times 3 September 2014: ''UKIP County Councillor resigns after being de-selected as Clacton election Candidate'' Accessed 8 September 2014] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905023744/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/essex_ukip_county_councillor_roger_lord_resigns_after_being_deselected_as_clacton_election_candidate_1_3755662 |date=5 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate was the actor and Tendring District councillor [[Giles Watling]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essexcountystandard.co.uk/news/localnews/11469050.Frinton_actor_Giles_Watling_named_as_Tory_candidate_for_by_election/?ref=var_0|title=Frinton actor Giles Watling named as Tory candidate for by-election|work=Essex County Standard|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> who was chosen by an [[Clacton open primary|open primary]] on 11 September. He was shortlisted with Colchester councillor Sue Lissimore.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11463392.BREAKING__Tory__open_primary__candidates_for_Clacton_by_election_are_Frinton_actor_Giles_Watling_and_Colchester_councillor_Sue_Lissimore/?ref=var_0 |title=TORY 'open primary' candidates for Clacton by-election are Frinton actor Giles Watling and Colchester councillor Sue Lissimore |last=Dwan |first=James |date=10 September 2014 |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423092906/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11463392.tory-open-primary-candidates-for-clacton-by-election-are-frinton-actor-giles-watling-and-colchester-councillor-sue-lissimore/ |url-status=live |archive-date=23 April 2020 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2014/09/two-candidates-shortlisted-for-the-clacton-by-election.html |title=Two candidates shortlisted for the Clacton by-election |last=Wallace |first=Mark |author-link=Mark Wallace (journalist) |date=10 September 2014 |website=Conservative Home |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423093246/http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2014/09/two-candidates-shortlisted-for-the-clacton-by-election.html |url-status=live |archive-date=23 April 2020 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Though he lost this by-election, he went on to win the seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] after Carswell stood down.\n\n[[Colchester]] councillor Tim Young had been announced prior to Carswell's resignation as candidate for [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/10848505.Tim_Young_selected_as_Labour_candidate_for_Clacton/?ref=rss |title=Tim Young selected as Labour candidate for Clacton |publisher=Gazette News |date=3 December 2013 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> and was confirmed as their by-election candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cllr_tim_young/status/505405737334747136 |title=Tim Young on Twitter: \"Delighted to have been endorsed as Labour's by-election candidate for Clacton. We'll be campaigning on the issues that really matter.\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29029022 |title=Clacton by-election to take place on 9 October |publisher=BBC News |date=2 September 2014 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberal Democrat candidate, Andy Graham, is the former mayor of [[Bishop's Stortford]] in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Stortford-mayor-Andy-Graham-fight-Clacton/story-22903376-detail/story.html|title=Former Stortford mayor Andy Graham to fight Clacton by-election for Lib Dems|work=Bishops Stortford Herts & Essex Observer|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref>  He is an actor as well as an author of children's books.<ref name=\"EADT 8-9-14\">[http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/poll_is_clacton_a_town_that_s_going_nowhere_1_3760753 Poll: Is Clacton a town that's going nowhere?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910180614/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/poll_is_clacton_a_town_that_s_going_nowhere_1_3760753 |date=10 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] candidate was Chris Southall.<ref name=\"clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11463330.Clacton_environmentalist_Chris_Southall_is_Green_Party_s_by_election_candidate/?ref=var_0|title=Clacton environmentalist Chris Southall is Green Party's by-election candidate|work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> Southall has stood for the Green Party over the last 40 years and gained some notoriety for a [[UFO]] hoax in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/southtoday/content/articles/2009/01/27/telltom_ufo_feature.shtml |title=Tell Tom - Are we alone? |publisher=BBC |date=18 February 2009 |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Howling Laud Hope|Alan \"Howling Laud\" Hope]] was the candidate for the [[Official Monster Raving Loony Party]]. He is also the leader of the party and the former mayor of [[Ashburton, Devon]].\n\n[[Charlotte Rose]] and Bruce Sizer were independent candidates.<ref name=eadt>{{cite news|last1=Lodge|first1=Will|title=Clacton: Candidates announced for Parliamentary by-election|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics_old_2_480/clacton_candidates_announced_for_parliamentary_by_election_1_3772859|accessdate=2 October 2014|work=[[East Anglian Daily Times]]|date=16 September 2014}}</ref>  Rose described herself as a \"high class [[courtesan]]\" campaigning \"for sexual freedom\".<ref>[http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11478019.Sex_worker_named_as_candidate_in_Clacton_by_election/ Sex worker named as candidate in Clacton by-election] Clacton and Frinton Gazette</ref> Sizer was a consultant oncologist at Colchester Hospital<ref>[http://www.specialistinfo.com/consget.php?con=sizeonco01 Profile] SpecialistInfo</ref><ref>[http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/press_release_pages/pr_030211.shtml Neil and Bec defy the odds to welcome Poppy into the world] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140918052923/http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/press_release_pages/pr_030211.shtml |date=18 September 2014 }} Colchester Hospital</ref> who stood as a single-issue candidate to get health and cancer care onto the agenda of the political parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex-ipswich-cancer-doctor-to-fight-clacton-by-election-on-health-agenda-1-3773826|title=Essex/Ipswich: Cancer doctor to fight Clacton by-election on health agenda|last=Lodge|first=Will|work=East Anglian Daily Times|access-date=27 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>  He was Joint Clinical Director of the Essex Cancer Network from 2006 until 2008 and is [[Oncology]] Editor for the Oxford Concise Medical Dictionary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr Bruce Sizer - Oncology|url=http://www.ramsayhealth.co.uk/consultants/oaks-hospital/oncology/dr-bruce-sizer|publisher=Ramsay Health Care UK|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\nThe Conservatives were mocked by UKIP supporters for sending out a leaflet, called \"The Big Clacton Survey\" asking voters to prioritise issues including \"local train and tube services\", despite the fact that the nearest tube (ie [[London Underground]]) station to Clacton is over {{convert|50|miles|km}} away.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/north_essex_news/11457629.Ukip_supporters_mock_Tory_survey_asking_Clacton_voters__views_on__local__tube_services/?ref=mr |title=Ukip supporters mock Tory survey asking Clacton voters' views on 'local' tube services |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=6 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111201/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11457629.ukip-supporters-mock-tory-survey-asking-clacton-voters-views-on-local-tube-services/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/06/ukip-douglas-carswell-clacton-campaign_n_5776998.html |title=Ukip\u2019s Douglas Carswell Tells Clacton: 'Don't Get Angry, Get Change' |last=Bennett |first=Asa |date=6 September 2014 |work=Huffington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422112215/https://consent.yahoo.com/collectConsent?sessionId=2_cc-session_6bef5d08-29f8-4978-b266-fb9ce1a3b019&lang=en-gb&inline=false |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> UKIP claimed to have recruited 150 local Conservative members after Carswell's defection.<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11450013.Ukip_claims__mass_exodus__of_Tory_party_members/?ref=mr |title=Ukip claims \"mass exodus\" of Tory party members |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=4 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111447/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11450013.ukip-claims-mass-exodus-of-tory-party-members/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe journalist and former Conservative MP, [[Matthew Parris]], created a controversy by writing in ''[[The Times]]'' that the Conservatives should be \"careless\" of Clacton voters\u2019 opinions as \"Clacton-on-Sea is going nowhere\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tories-should-turn-their-backs-on-clacton-j0k5h6zld08 |title=Tories should turn their backs on Clacton |last=Parris |first=Matthew |date=6 September 2014 |work=The Times |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422110216/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tories-should-turn-their-backs-on-clacton-j0k5h6zld08 |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11082586/The-voters-of-Clacton-dont-deserve-Matthew-Parriss-sneering-contempt.html |title=The voters of Clacton don't deserve Mr Parris's sneering contempt |last1=Ford |first1=Rob |last2=Goodwin |first2=Matthew |author-link2=Matthew Goodwin |date=8 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422105921/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11082586/The-voters-of-Clacton-dont-deserve-Matthew-Parriss-sneering-contempt.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/timstanley/100285407/dear-matthew-parris-if-the-tories-abandon-the-working-class-to-ukip-they-will-deserve-to-lose-2015/ |title=If the Tories abandon the working class to UKIP they deserve to lose |last=Stanley |first=Tim |author-link=Tim Stanley |date=6 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913154003/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/timstanley/100285407/dear-matthew-parris-if-the-tories-abandon-the-working-class-to-ukip-they-will-deserve-to-lose-2015/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 September 2014 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> remarks which were disowned by local Conservatives and denounced by Carswell as \"reflective of what so many in the upper echelons of the Tory party really think\"<ref name = \"EADT 8-9-14\"/> and were cited by two local Conservative councillors as a reason for defecting to UKIP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/north_essex_news/11462031.Two_Clacton_Tory_councillors_defect_to_Ukip/?ref=mr |title=Two Clacton Tory councillors defect to Ukip |last=Dwan |first=James |date=9 September 2014 |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111018/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11462031.two-clacton-tory-councillors-defect-to-ukip/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn important component of the UKIP campaign was a public meeting of 700 people at the [[Clacton Coastal Academy]] with [[Douglas Carswell]] and UKIP leader [[Nigel Farage]] which was billed as the \"biggest public meeting in Clacton in living memory\".<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11488568.More_than_700_people_snap_up_tickets_for__biggest_public_meeting_in_Clacton_in_living_memory__with_Ukip_leader_Nigel_Farage/?ref=var_0 |title=More than 700 people snap up tickets for \"biggest public meeting in Clacton in living memory\" with Ukip leader Nigel Farage |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=22 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111722/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11488568.more-than-700-people-snap-up-tickets-for-biggest-public-meeting-in-clacton-in-living-memory-with-ukip-leader-nigel-farage/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/11bf9abc-449e-11e4-bce8-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3EYRb94Wm |title=Ukip takes anti-establishment fight to Essex seaside |last=Thompson |first=Barney |date=25 September 2014 |work=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11121526/Is-Ukips-Douglas-Carswell-overshadowing-Nigel-Farage-within-the-party.html |title=Is Ukip's Douglas Carswell overshadowing Nigel Farage within the party? |last1=Hayes |first1=Kat |last2=Akkoc |first2=Raziye |date=26 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422110548/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11121526/Is-Ukips-Douglas-Carswell-overshadowing-Nigel-Farage-within-the-party.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoth the Prime Minister [[David Cameron]]<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/north_essex_news/11510833.David_Cameron_says__underdog__Tories_can_win_Clacton_by_election_during_visit_to_resort/?ref=mr |title=David Cameron says 'underdog' Tories can win Clacton by-election during visit to resort |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=2 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111903/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11510833.david-cameron-says-underdog-tories-can-win-clacton-by-election-during-visit-to-resort/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> and the Labour leader [[Ed Miliband]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11509908.Labour_leader_Miliband____we_re_the_party_to_tackle_GP_shortage_/?ref=mr |title=Clacton: Labour leader Miliband - 'we're the party to tackle GP shortage' |last=Dwan |first=James |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=2 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422112008/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11509908.clacton-labour-leader-miliband-were-the-party-to-tackle-gp-shortage/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> visited the constituency to help their respective party campaigns.\n\nTen days before the election, the artist [[Banksy]] painted a mural on a wall in Clacton which showed five grey pigeons holding three placards. They held the words \"go back to Africa\"  \"migrants not welcome\", and \"keep off our worms\". They were directed towards a more colourful migratory swallow perched further along the same wire.  The mural was removed by [[Tendring District Council]] who had  received a complaint that \"offensive and racist remarks\" had appeared on a wall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/oct/01/banksy-mural-clacton-racist |title=Council removes Banksy artwork after complaints of racism |last=Johnston |first=Chris |date=1 October 2014 |work=The Guardian |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422110701/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/oct/01/banksy-mural-clacton-racist |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Polling==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:14px\"\n|-\n!! style=\"width:75px;\"| Date(s)<br/>conducted!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Polling organisation/client!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Sample size!! class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#0087dc; width:60px;\"| [[Conservative Party (UK)|<span style=\"color:White;\">Con</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#dc241f; width:60px;\"| [[Labour Party (UK)|<span style=\"color:White;\">Lab</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#70147a; width:60px;\"| [[UK Independence Party|<span style=\"color:White;\">UKIP</span>]]!!class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#fdbb30; width:60px;\"| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|<span style=\"color:Black;\">LD</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:#9c3; width:60px;\"|[[Green Party of England and Wales|<span style=\"color:White;\">Green</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:gray; width:60px;\"| [[List of political parties in the United Kingdom|<span style=\"color:White;\">Others</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:85px;\"| Lead\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|'''9 Oct 2014''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| '''Clacton by-election Result'''  ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|''35,365''||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 24.6% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 11.2% || style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"|  '''59.7%''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.4% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.9% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.2% || style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''35.1%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| 29 Aug \u2013 1 Sep || [http://lordashcroftpolls.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Clacton-poll-Full-data-tables-September-2014.pdf Lord Ashcroft]  ([[2015 United Kingdom general election|for the next General Election]]) || 1,001 || 27% || 19% || style=\"background:plum\"|  '''48%''' || 3% || 3% ||<0.5%|| style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''21%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| 29 Aug \u2013 1 Sep || [http://lordashcroftpolls.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Clacton-poll-Full-data-tables-September-2014.pdf Lord Ashcroft] (for the 2014 by-election) || 1,001 || 24% || 16% || style=\"background:plum\"|  '''56%''' || 2% || 1% || 1% || style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''32%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| 28\u201329 Aug || Survation (for the 2014 by-election)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/Clacton-constituency-poll-results.zip |title=Survation }}</ref> || 700 || 20% || 13% || style=\"background:plum\"|  '''64%''' || 2% || 1% ||<0.5%|| style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''44%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|'''6 May 2010''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/default.stm General Election Results]  ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| ''43,123'' || style=\"background:#0087dc; color:white;\" | '''53.0%''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 25.0% || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| - ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 12.9% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.2% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 7.8% || style=\"background:#0087dc; color:white;\"| '''28.0%''' <small>over Lab</small>\n|}\n\n==Result==\n{{Election box begin|title=By-election 2014: Clacton}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n  |votes      = 21,113\n  |percentage = 59.7\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Giles Watling]]\n  |votes      = 8,709\n  |percentage = 24.6\n  |change     = {{decrease}} 28.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Tim Young\n  |votes      = 3,957\n  |percentage = 11.2\n  |change     = {{decrease}} 13.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Chris Southall\n  |votes      = 688\n  |percentage = 1.9\n  |change     = {{increase}} 0.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Andrew Graham\n  |votes      = 483\n  |percentage = 1.4\n  |change     = {{decrease}} 11.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n  |party      = Independent\n  |candidate  = Bruce Sizer\n  |votes      = 205\n  |percentage = 0.6\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Official Monster Raving Loony Party\n  |candidate  =  [[Howling Laud Hope|Alan \"Howling Laud\" Hope]]\n  |votes      = 127\n  |percentage = 0.4\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n  |party      = Independent\n  |candidate  = [[Charlotte Rose]]\n  |votes      = 56\n  |percentage = 0.2\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  |votes      = 12,404\n  |percentage = 35.1\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  |votes      = 35,338\n  |percentage = 51\n  |change     = \n}} \n{{Election box gain with party link\n |winner     = UK Independence Party\n |loser      = Conservative Party (UK)\n |swing      = {{increase}} 44.1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nThe election produced a number of [[United Kingdom by-election records|statistical records]], partly because of the unusual situation in which an incumbent MP with a large majority for one party has resigned and then stood for re-election on behalf of a new party for which support was in any case on a strongly rising trend. The 59.7% increase in the percentage vote achieved by UKIP since the previous general election (when they did not field a candidate) is the greatest ever in British parliamentary elections, although the percentage swing remains 0.1% less than the record 44.2% swing to the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] at the [[1983 Bermondsey by-election]].  The 28.4% reduction in Conservative votes is the 16th worst for any party since the Second World War, while the 1.4% of the vote achieved by the Liberal Democrats was, at the time, the third smallest vote ever obtained by a major party, and the worst since [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite interview |last=Curtice |first=John |subject-link=John Curtice |interviewer=[[Andrew Neil]] |title=Clacton by-election: Statistics of Douglas Carswell's win |type=Video |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29563847 |publisher=BBC News |date=10 October 2014 |access-date = 22 April 2014}}</ref> Since then, however, the Liberal Democrats received an even smaller proportion of the vote at the [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|Rochester and Strood by-election]] later in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rochester-byelection-lib-dems-blame-tactical-voting-for-partys-worst-ever-result-9876694.html |title=Rochester by-election: Lib Dems blame tactical voting for party\u2019s worst ever result |last=McSmith |first=Andy |work=The Independent |date=21 November 2014  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221093022/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rochester-byelection-lib-dems-blame-tactical-voting-for-partys-worst-ever-result-9876694.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 December 2014 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Previous result==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|General election 2010]]: Clacton<ref name=2010result>{{cite news |title=Clacton |first= |last= |newspaper=[[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2010 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b14.stm }}</ref>}}\n\nUKIP did not stand a candidate against Douglas Carswell in 2010, citing his Eurosceptic views.\n\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n|party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n|votes      = 22,867\n|percentage = 53.0\n|change     = {{increase}} 8.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Ivan Henderson]]\n|votes      = 10,799\n|percentage = 25.0\n|change     = {{decrease}} 10.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n|candidate  = Michael Green\n|votes      = 5,577\n|percentage = 12.9\n|change     = {{decrease}} 0.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = British National Party\n|candidate  = Jim Taylor\n|votes      = 1,975\n|percentage = 4.6\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n|party      = Tendring First\n|candidate  = Terry Allen\n|votes      = 1,078\n|percentage = 2.5\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n|candidate  = Chris Southall\n|votes      = 535\n|percentage = 1.2\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Independent (politician)\n|candidate  = Chris Humphrey\n|votes      = 292\n|percentage = 0.7\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n|votes      = 12,068\n|percentage = 28.0\n|change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n|votes      = 43,123\n|percentage = 64.2\n|change     = {{increase}} 1.6\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n|winner = Conservative Party (UK)\n|swing  = {{increase}} 9.7\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics|United Kingdom}}\n*[[2015 United Kingdom general election]]\n*[[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of United Kingdom by-elections (2010\u2013present)]]\n*[[Opinion polling for the 2015 United Kingdom general election]]\n*[[Opinion polling for the 2015 United Kingdom general election in individual constituencies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{By-elections to the 55th UK Parliament}}\n{{Brexit topics|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2014 in England|Clacton by-election]]\n[[Category:2014 elections in the United Kingdom|Clacton by-election]]\n[[Category:October 2014 events in the United Kingdom|Clacton by-election]]\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in Essex constituencies]]\n[[Category:Tendring]]\n[[Category:2010s in Essex]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2014 Clacton by-election\n| type = parliamentary\n| country = United Kingdom\n| seats_for_election = [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]] constituency\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2010 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year = 2010\n| next_election = 2015 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year = 2015\n| election_date = 9 October 2014\n| candidate1 = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n| image1 =  [[File:Douglas Carswell.jpg|160x160px]]\n| party1 = UK Independence Party\n| last_election1 = \n| popular_vote1 = '''21,113'''\n| percentage1 = '''59.7%'''\n| swing1 = ''New party''\n| candidate2 = [[Giles Watling]]\n| image2 = [[File:Official portrait of Giles Watling crop 2.jpg|160x160px]]\n| party2 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| last_election2 =  \n| popular_vote2 = 8,709\n| percentage2 = 24.6%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}}28.4%\n| candidate3 = Tim Young\n| image3 = [[File:No image.svg|110px]]\n| party3 = Labour Party (UK)\n| last_election3 = \n| popular_vote3 = 3,957\n| percentage3 = 11.2%\n| swing3 = {{decrease}}13.8%\n| map_image = Clacton2007Constituency.svg\n| map_size = 150px\n| map_caption = Map showing the [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]] Parliamentary constituency within the [[England|English]] county of [[Essex]].\n| title = MP\n| posttitle = Subsequent MP\n| before_election = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n| before_party = Conservative Party (UK)\n| after_election = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n| after_party = UK Independence Party\n}}\n\nThe '''Clacton by-election''' was held on 9 October 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29029022 |title=Clacton by-election to be held on 9 October |publisher=BBC News |date=2014-09-02 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> for the [[United Kingdom]] [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] of [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|Clacton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/update/2014-08-29/chancellor-makes-douglas-carswells-resignation-official/ |title=Chancellor makes Douglas Carswell's resignation official |publisher=Itv.com |date=2014-08-29 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref><ref name = \"BBC_29_Aug\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28977961 |title=Stuart Wheeler: More Tory defections to UKIP 'odds on' |publisher=BBC News |date=2014-08-29 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Swinford |first=Steven |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11060963/Douglas-Carswells-shock-defection-to-Ukip-triggers-by-election-battle.html |title=Douglas Carswell's shock defection to UKIP triggers by-election battle |publisher=Telegraph |date=2014-08-28 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-08-29/carswell-and-farage-in-clacton-ahead-of-by-election/ |title=ITV News Carswell and Farage in Clacton Ahead of by-election |publisher=Itv.com |date=2014-08-29 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> The by-election was triggered by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP for Clacton, [[Douglas Carswell]], defecting to the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) and subsequently [[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resigning]] his seat to seek re-election as its candidate.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nicholas |last=Watt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/28/douglas-carswell-ukip-defects-tory-mp-byelection |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell defects to Ukip and forces byelection |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2014-08-28 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref>\n\nStanding for UKIP, Carswell retained the seat with 59.7% of the vote, becoming UKIP's first elected MP. The Conservatives came second, and Labour third.  According to [[John Curtice]], professor of politics at [[Strathclyde University]], the result was the biggest increase in the share of a vote for any party in any by-election in history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b912186e-504f-11e4-8645-00144feab7de.html |title=Ukip surge sends tremors through Westminster |last1=Pickard |first1=Jim |last2=Odell |first2=Mark |date=10 October 2014 |work=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Douglas Carswell, May 2009.jpg|thumb|left|[[Douglas Carswell]] defected from the Conservatives to UKIP and triggered the by-election by resigning his seat]]\nOn 28 August 2014 Carswell, a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] backbencher, announced his defection to UKIP and said that he was resigning his seat in order to fight a by-election. He said he did not think Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] was \"serious about the change we need\", adding that \"many of those at the top of the Conservative Party are simply not on our side\" and \"Of course they talk the talk before elections. They say what they feel they must say to get our support when they want our support, but on so many issues \u2013 on modernising our politics, on the recall of MPs, on controlling our borders[,] on less government, on bank reform, on cutting public debt, on an EU referendum \u2013 they never actually make it happen\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28967904 |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell defects to UKIP and forces by-election |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=28 August 2014 |publisher=BBC News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422133403/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28967904 |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}.</ref> He also said: \"...local issues regarding planning and overcrowding of GP surgeries were a factor in my decision to resign\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11439315._Local_issues_affected_my_decision__claims_Carswell_following_defection_to_UKIP/?ref=var_0 |title=\"Local issues affected my decision\" claims Carswell following defection to UKIP |first=James |last=Dwan |date=28 August 2014 |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422185234/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11439315.local-issues-affected-my-decision-claims-carswell-following-defection-to-ukip/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nResponding to the news that Carswell had defected and would trigger a by-election, Cameron said the contest would be held \"as soon as possible\". He also confirmed that the Conservatives would contest the by-election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28967904 |title=Tory MP Douglas Carswell defects to UKIP and forces by-election |publisher=BBC News |date=2014-08-28 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> It was later announced that the by-election would be held on 9 October, which was also Cameron's 48th birthday. The poll was one of two parliamentary by-elections the same day, with [[2014 Heywood and Middleton by-election|an election]] also being held in the constituency of [[Heywood and Middleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Heywood and Middleton]] following the death of its MP, [[Jim Dobbin]] of Labour.<ref name=clacton>{{cite news|last1=Oliver|first1=Joe|title=By-election battle: Fight for late MP Jim Dobbin's Heywood and Middleton seat begins before he is buried|url=http://www.mancunianmatters.co.uk/content/120970652-election-battle-fight-late-mp-jim-dobbins-heywood-and-middleton-seat-begins-he|work=Mancunian Matters|date=12 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnalysis of [[demographics]] for the constituency prior to the by-election were said to make it the most UKIP-friendly in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Osborn |first=Andrew|title=UKIP poised to snare first parliament seat in blow to Cameron |date=9 October 2014|work=The Independent|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/10/08/uk-britain-politics-idUKKCN0HX2H420141008|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Conservative reaction==\nThere was speculation that [[Boris Johnson]], the Conservative [[Mayor of London]], would seek the candidacy at the by-election. On 29 August 2014, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' journalist [[Peter Oborne]] wrote that: \"David Cameron should go down on his knees and beg Boris Johnson to stand as the Conservative Party's candidate for Clacton in the coming by-election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/peteroborne/100284436/why-david-cameron-must-beg-boris-johnson-to-fight-in-calcton/ |title=Why David Cameron must beg Boris Johnson to fight in Clacton |last=Oborne |first=Peter |date=29 August 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017021923/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/peteroborne/100284436/why-david-cameron-must-beg-boris-johnson-to-fight-in-calcton/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> The bookmaker [[Ladbrokes]] offered odds of 33-1 against Johnson standing in Clacton.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mylondon.news/news/local-news/uxbridge-lose-boris-johnson-clacton-7690859 |title=Will Uxbridge lose Boris Johnson to Clacton seat? |last=Drewett |first=Zoe |date=29 August 2014 |publisher=MyLondon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422132843/https://www.mylondon.news/news/local-news/uxbridge-lose-boris-johnson-clacton-7690859 |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> He ruled out standing, saying that he was intent on fighting [[Uxbridge and South Ruislip (UK Parliament constituency)|Uxbridge and South Ruislip]] at the general election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/02/boris-johnson-clacton-carswell-ukip_n_5750712.html |title=Boris Johnson Rules Out Fighting Douglas Carswell For Clacton |last=Simons |first=Ned |date=2 September 2014 |work=Huffington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422133118/https://consent.yahoo.com/collectConsent?sessionId=2_cc-session_62807458-f846-47e6-be5b-7a2fed3c316e&lang=en-gb&inline=false |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile many Conservatives condemned Carswell's defection, some were more supportive of him. Conservative backbencher [[Nigel Evans]] suggested that possibly the Conservatives should not stand in Clacton.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nicholas |last=Watt |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/31/tories-ukip-clacton-byelection-douglas-carswell?CMP=twt_gu |title=Tories should give Ukip free run in Clacton, MP suggests |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2014-08-31 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> Former minister [[Norman Tebbit]] refused to campaign against Carswell and claimed that the \"House of Commons needs men like [[Douglas Carswell]]\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Norman |last=Tebbit |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/normantebbit/100284355/the-house-of-commons-needs-men-like-douglas-carswell-i-would-not-campaign-against-him/ |title=The House of Commons needs men like Douglas Carswell: I would not campaign against him |publisher=Blogs.telegraph.co.uk |date=2014-08-28 |accessdate=2014-09-06}}</ref> Backbencher [[Zac Goldsmith]] described Carswell as a \"model Parliamentarian\" and remarked that \"I have nothing but admiration for him\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11060963/Douglas-Carswells-shock-defection-to-Ukip-triggers-by-election-battle.html |title=Douglas Carswell's shock defection to Ukip triggers by-election battle |last1=Swinford |first1=Steven |last2=Holehouse |first2=Matthew |date=28 August 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422185747/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11060963/Douglas-Carswells-shock-defection-to-Ukip-triggers-by-election-battle.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Nick Herbert]], the former policing minister, said that the Conservative Party was more concerned with the Clacton by-election rather than winning the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]] that was held during the early part of the Clacton campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Swinford |first=Steven |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scottish-independence/11107017/Tory-MPs-expected-to-buy-ice-creams-in-Clacton-instead-of-going-to-Scotland.html |title=Tory MPs expected to 'buy ice-creams in Clacton' instead of going to Scotland |date=18 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422185942/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scottish-independence/11107017/Tory-MPs-expected-to-buy-ice-creams-in-Clacton-instead-of-going-to-Scotland.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\nDuring the campaign, a second Conservative MP and close friend of Carswell,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-29395030 |title=Conservative MP Mark Reckless defects to UKIP |publisher=BBC News |date=2014-09-27 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> [[Mark Reckless]], likewise defected to UKIP and sought re-election in a [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|by-election]] for his constituency of [[Rochester and Strood (UK Parliament constituency)|Rochester and Strood]].\n\n==Candidates==\n[[Tendring District Council]], the local authority administering the by-election, confirmed the deadline for nominations as 4 pm on 16 September 2014.<ref>[http://www.tendringdc.gov.uk/council/elections-voting/clacton-constituency-parliamentary-election Clacton constituency parliamentary by-election] Tendring District Council</ref>\n\nCarswell announced that he would stand again for the seat as UKIP's candidate, although he was opposed by the recently selected UKIP candidate, Roger Lord,<ref>{{cite web|last=Holehouse |first=Matthew |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11065185/Douglas-Carswell-is-a-gutless-coward-says-ousted-UKIP-candidate-Roger-Lord.html |title='Douglas Carswell is a gutless coward' says ousted UKIP candidate Roger Lord |publisher=Telegraph |date=2014-08-29 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> with some local activists speculating that they might not adopt Carswell. Anne Poonian, secretary of Clacton UKIP association, was quoted by [[Buzzfeed]] saying that, although she welcomed Carswell's decision to defect, he may not be selected.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jimwaterson/ukips-clacton-candidate-says-he-wont-stand-down-for-douglas |title=UKIP's Clacton Candidate Says He Won't Stand Down For Douglas Carswell |last=Waterson |first=Jim |date=28 August 2014 |publisher=BuzzFeed News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423093530/https://www.buzzfeed.com/jimwaterson/ukips-clacton-candidate-says-he-wont-stand-down-for-douglas |url-status=live |archive-date=23 April 2020 |access-date=23 April 2020 |quote='Carswell's taking a very big risk for getting in for a little party. We may not adopt him as our candidate, who knows? He has to be adopted by us, the local association. At the moment he\u2019s just an unemployed MP. Who knows whether he\u2019ll be adopted?'}}</ref> However, UKIP rules for selecting by-election candidates invested the decision with the National Executive Committee, which selected Carswell.<ref name = \"BBC_29_Aug\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politicshome.com/uk/story/44030/ukip_candidate_blasts_stupid_carswell.html |title=Ukip candidate blasts 'stupid' Carswell |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=29 August 2014 |website=PoliticsHome |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903131533/http://www.politicshome.com/uk/story/44030/ukip_candidate_blasts_stupid_carswell.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 September 2014 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Lord left UKIP and resigned his County Council seat, supporting the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] in the council by-election.<ref name=\"EADT1\">[http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/essex_ukip_county_councillor_roger_lord_resigns_after_being_deselected_as_clacton_election_candidate_1_3755662 East Anglian Daily Times 3 September 2014: ''UKIP County Councillor resigns after being de-selected as Clacton election Candidate'' Accessed 8 September 2014] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905023744/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/essex_ukip_county_councillor_roger_lord_resigns_after_being_deselected_as_clacton_election_candidate_1_3755662 |date=5 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidate was the actor and Tendring District councillor [[Giles Watling]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essexcountystandard.co.uk/news/localnews/11469050.Frinton_actor_Giles_Watling_named_as_Tory_candidate_for_by_election/?ref=var_0|title=Frinton actor Giles Watling named as Tory candidate for by-election|work=Essex County Standard|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> who was chosen by an [[Clacton open primary|open primary]] on 11 September. He was shortlisted with Colchester councillor Sue Lissimore.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11463392.BREAKING__Tory__open_primary__candidates_for_Clacton_by_election_are_Frinton_actor_Giles_Watling_and_Colchester_councillor_Sue_Lissimore/?ref=var_0 |title=TORY 'open primary' candidates for Clacton by-election are Frinton actor Giles Watling and Colchester councillor Sue Lissimore |last=Dwan |first=James |date=10 September 2014 |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423092906/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11463392.tory-open-primary-candidates-for-clacton-by-election-are-frinton-actor-giles-watling-and-colchester-councillor-sue-lissimore/ |url-status=live |archive-date=23 April 2020 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2014/09/two-candidates-shortlisted-for-the-clacton-by-election.html |title=Two candidates shortlisted for the Clacton by-election |last=Wallace |first=Mark |author-link=Mark Wallace (journalist) |date=10 September 2014 |website=Conservative Home |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423093246/http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2014/09/two-candidates-shortlisted-for-the-clacton-by-election.html |url-status=live |archive-date=23 April 2020 |access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref> Though he lost this by-election, he went on to win the seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] after Carswell stood down.\n\n[[Colchester]] councillor Tim Young had been announced prior to Carswell's resignation as candidate for [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/10848505.Tim_Young_selected_as_Labour_candidate_for_Clacton/?ref=rss |title=Tim Young selected as Labour candidate for Clacton |publisher=Gazette News |date=2013-12-03 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref> and was confirmed as their by-election candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cllr_tim_young/status/505405737334747136 |title=Tim Young on Twitter: \"Delighted to have been endorsed as Labour's by-election candidate for Clacton. We'll be campaigning on the issues that really matter.\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29029022 |title=Clacton by-election to take place on 9 October |publisher=BBC News |date=2014-09-02 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Liberal Democrat candidate, Andy Graham, is the former mayor of [[Bishop's Stortford]] in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Stortford-mayor-Andy-Graham-fight-Clacton/story-22903376-detail/story.html|title=Former Stortford mayor Andy Graham to fight Clacton by-election for Lib Dems|work=Bishops Stortford Herts & Essex Observer|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref>  He is an actor as well as an author of children's books.<ref name=\"EADT 8-9-14\">[http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/poll_is_clacton_a_town_that_s_going_nowhere_1_3760753 Poll: Is Clacton a town that's going nowhere?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910180614/http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics-old/poll_is_clacton_a_town_that_s_going_nowhere_1_3760753 |date=10 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] candidate was Chris Southall.<ref name=\"clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11463330.Clacton_environmentalist_Chris_Southall_is_Green_Party_s_by_election_candidate/?ref=var_0|title=Clacton environmentalist Chris Southall is Green Party's by-election candidate|work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> Southall has stood for the Green Party over the last 40 years and gained some notoriety for a [[UFO]] hoax in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/southtoday/content/articles/2009/01/27/telltom_ufo_feature.shtml |title=Tell Tom - Are we alone? |publisher=BBC |date=2009-02-18 |accessdate=2016-08-25}}</ref>\n\n[[Howling Laud Hope|Alan \"Howling Laud\" Hope]] was the candidate for the [[Official Monster Raving Loony Party]]. He is also the leader of the party and the former mayor of [[Ashburton, Devon]].\n\n[[Charlotte Rose]] and Bruce Sizer were independent candidates.<ref name=eadt>{{cite news|last1=Lodge|first1=Will|title=Clacton: Candidates announced for Parliamentary by-election|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/politics_old_2_480/clacton_candidates_announced_for_parliamentary_by_election_1_3772859|accessdate=2 October 2014|work=[[East Anglian Daily Times]]|date=16 September 2014}}</ref>  Rose described herself as a \"high class [[courtesan]]\" campaigning \"for sexual freedom\".<ref>[http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11478019.Sex_worker_named_as_candidate_in_Clacton_by_election/ Sex worker named as candidate in Clacton by-election] Clacton and Frinton Gazette</ref> Sizer was a consultant oncologist at Colchester Hospital<ref>[http://www.specialistinfo.com/consget.php?con=sizeonco01 Profile] SpecialistInfo</ref><ref>[http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/press_release_pages/pr_030211.shtml Neil and Bec defy the odds to welcome Poppy into the world] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140918052923/http://www.colchesterhospital.nhs.uk/press_release_pages/pr_030211.shtml |date=18 September 2014 }} Colchester Hospital</ref> who stood as a single-issue candidate to get health and cancer care onto the agenda of the political parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/essex-ipswich-cancer-doctor-to-fight-clacton-by-election-on-health-agenda-1-3773826|title=Essex/Ipswich: Cancer doctor to fight Clacton by-election on health agenda|last=Lodge|first=Will|work=East Anglian Daily Times|access-date=2017-07-27|language=en}}</ref>  He was Joint Clinical Director of the Essex Cancer Network from 2006 until 2008 and is [[Oncology]] Editor for the Oxford Concise Medical Dictionary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr Bruce Sizer - Oncology|url=http://www.ramsayhealth.co.uk/consultants/oaks-hospital/oncology/dr-bruce-sizer|publisher=Ramsay Health Care UK|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Campaign==\nThe Conservatives were mocked by UKIP supporters for sending out a leaflet, called \"The Big Clacton Survey\" asking voters to prioritise issues including \"local train and tube services\", despite the fact that the nearest tube (ie [[London Underground]]) station to Clacton is over {{convert|50|miles|km}} away.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/north_essex_news/11457629.Ukip_supporters_mock_Tory_survey_asking_Clacton_voters__views_on__local__tube_services/?ref=mr |title=Ukip supporters mock Tory survey asking Clacton voters' views on 'local' tube services |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=6 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111201/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11457629.ukip-supporters-mock-tory-survey-asking-clacton-voters-views-on-local-tube-services/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/06/ukip-douglas-carswell-clacton-campaign_n_5776998.html |title=Ukip\u2019s Douglas Carswell Tells Clacton: 'Don't Get Angry, Get Change' |last=Bennett |first=Asa |date=6 September 2014 |work=Huffington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422112215/https://consent.yahoo.com/collectConsent?sessionId=2_cc-session_6bef5d08-29f8-4978-b266-fb9ce1a3b019&lang=en-gb&inline=false |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> UKIP claimed to have recruited 150 local Conservative members after Carswell's defection.<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11450013.Ukip_claims__mass_exodus__of_Tory_party_members/?ref=mr |title=Ukip claims \"mass exodus\" of Tory party members |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=4 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111447/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11450013.ukip-claims-mass-exodus-of-tory-party-members/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe journalist and former Conservative MP, [[Matthew Parris]], created a controversy by writing in ''[[The Times]]'' that the Conservatives should be \"careless\" of Clacton voters\u2019 opinions as \"Clacton-on-Sea is going nowhere\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tories-should-turn-their-backs-on-clacton-j0k5h6zld08 |title=Tories should turn their backs on Clacton |last=Parris |first=Matthew |date=6 September 2014 |work=The Times |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422110216/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tories-should-turn-their-backs-on-clacton-j0k5h6zld08 |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11082586/The-voters-of-Clacton-dont-deserve-Matthew-Parriss-sneering-contempt.html |title=The voters of Clacton don't deserve Mr Parris's sneering contempt |last1=Ford |first1=Rob |last2=Goodwin |first2=Matthew |author-link2=Matthew Goodwin |date=8 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422105921/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11082586/The-voters-of-Clacton-dont-deserve-Matthew-Parriss-sneering-contempt.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/timstanley/100285407/dear-matthew-parris-if-the-tories-abandon-the-working-class-to-ukip-they-will-deserve-to-lose-2015/ |title=If the Tories abandon the working class to UKIP they deserve to lose |last=Stanley |first=Tim |author-link=Tim Stanley |date=6 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913154003/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/timstanley/100285407/dear-matthew-parris-if-the-tories-abandon-the-working-class-to-ukip-they-will-deserve-to-lose-2015/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 September 2014 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> remarks which were disowned by local Conservatives and denounced by Carswell as \"reflective of what so many in the upper echelons of the Tory party really think\"<ref name = \"EADT 8-9-14\"/> and were cited by two local Conservative councillors as a reason for defecting to UKIP.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/north_essex_news/11462031.Two_Clacton_Tory_councillors_defect_to_Ukip/?ref=mr |title=Two Clacton Tory councillors defect to Ukip |last=Dwan |first=James |date=9 September 2014 |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111018/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11462031.two-clacton-tory-councillors-defect-to-ukip/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn important component of the UKIP campaign was a public meeting of 700 people at the [[Clacton Coastal Academy]] with [[Douglas Carswell]] and UKIP leader [[Nigel Farage]] which was billed as the \"biggest public meeting in Clacton in living memory\".<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11488568.More_than_700_people_snap_up_tickets_for__biggest_public_meeting_in_Clacton_in_living_memory__with_Ukip_leader_Nigel_Farage/?ref=var_0 |title=More than 700 people snap up tickets for \"biggest public meeting in Clacton in living memory\" with Ukip leader Nigel Farage |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=22 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111722/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11488568.more-than-700-people-snap-up-tickets-for-biggest-public-meeting-in-clacton-in-living-memory-with-ukip-leader-nigel-farage/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/11bf9abc-449e-11e4-bce8-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3EYRb94Wm |title=Ukip takes anti-establishment fight to Essex seaside |last=Thompson |first=Barney |date=25 September 2014 |work=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11121526/Is-Ukips-Douglas-Carswell-overshadowing-Nigel-Farage-within-the-party.html |title=Is Ukip's Douglas Carswell overshadowing Nigel Farage within the party? |last1=Hayes |first1=Kat |last2=Akkoc |first2=Raziye |date=26 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422110548/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/11121526/Is-Ukips-Douglas-Carswell-overshadowing-Nigel-Farage-within-the-party.html |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoth the Prime Minister [[David Cameron]]<ref>{{cite web|first=James |last=Dwan |url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/north_essex_news/11510833.David_Cameron_says__underdog__Tories_can_win_Clacton_by_election_during_visit_to_resort/?ref=mr |title=David Cameron says 'underdog' Tories can win Clacton by-election during visit to resort |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=2 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422111903/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11510833.david-cameron-says-underdog-tories-can-win-clacton-by-election-during-visit-to-resort/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> and the Labour leader [[Ed Miliband]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11509908.Labour_leader_Miliband____we_re_the_party_to_tackle_GP_shortage_/?ref=mr |title=Clacton: Labour leader Miliband - 'we're the party to tackle GP shortage' |last=Dwan |first=James |work=Clacton and Frinton Gazette |date=2 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422112008/https://www.clactonandfrintongazette.co.uk/news/11509908.clacton-labour-leader-miliband-were-the-party-to-tackle-gp-shortage/ |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> visited the constituency to help their respective party campaigns.\n\nTen days before the election, the artist [[Banksy]] painted a mural on a wall in Clacton which showed five grey pigeons holding three placards. They held the words \"go back to Africa\"  \"migrants not welcome\", and \"keep off our worms\". They were directed towards a more colourful migratory swallow perched further along the same wire.  The mural was removed by [[Tendring District Council]] who had  received a complaint that \"offensive and racist remarks\" had appeared on a wall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/oct/01/banksy-mural-clacton-racist |title=Council removes Banksy artwork after complaints of racism |last=Johnston |first=Chris |date=1 October 2014 |work=The Guardian |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422110701/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/oct/01/banksy-mural-clacton-racist |url-status=live |archive-date=22 April 2020 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Polling==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:14px\"\n|-\n!! style=\"width:75px;\"| Date(s)<br/>conducted!! style=\"width:200px;\"|Polling organisation/client!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Sample size!! class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#0087dc; width:60px;\"| [[Conservative Party (UK)|<span style=\"color:White;\">Con</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#dc241f; width:60px;\"| [[Labour Party (UK)|<span style=\"color:White;\">Lab</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#70147a; width:60px;\"| [[UK Independence Party|<span style=\"color:White;\">UKIP</span>]]!!class=\"unsortable\"  style=\"background:#fdbb30; width:60px;\"| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|<span style=\"color:Black;\">LD</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:#9c3; width:60px;\"|[[Green Party of England and Wales|<span style=\"color:White;\">Green</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:gray; width:60px;\"| [[List of political parties in the United Kingdom|<span style=\"color:White;\">Others</span>]]!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:85px;\"| Lead\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|'''9 Oct 2014''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| '''Clacton by-election Result'''  ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|''35,365''||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 24.6% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 11.2% || style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"|  '''59.7%''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.4% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.9% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.2% || style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''35.1%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| 29 Aug\u20131 Sep || [http://lordashcroftpolls.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Clacton-poll-Full-data-tables-September-2014.pdf Lord Ashcroft]  ([[2015 United Kingdom general election|for the next General Election]]) || 1,001 || 27% || 19% || style=\"background:plum\"|  '''48%''' || 3% || 3% ||<0.5%|| style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''21%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| 29 Aug\u20131 Sep || [http://lordashcroftpolls.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Clacton-poll-Full-data-tables-September-2014.pdf Lord Ashcroft] (for the 2014 by-election) || 1,001 || 24% || 16% || style=\"background:plum\"|  '''56%''' || 2% || 1% || 1% || style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''32%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| 28\u201329 Aug || Survation (for the 2014 by-election)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/Clacton-constituency-poll-results.zip |title=Survation }}</ref> || 700 || 20% || 13% || style=\"background:plum\"|  '''64%''' || 2% || 1% ||<0.5%|| style=\"background:#70147a; color:white;\"| '''44%''' <small>over Con</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|'''6 May 2010''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/default.stm General Election Results]  ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| ''43,123'' || style=\"background:#0087dc; color:white;\" | '''53.0%''' ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 25.0% || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| - ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 12.9% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 1.2% ||style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| 7.8% || style=\"background:#0087dc; color:white;\"| '''28.0%''' <small>over Lab</small>\n|}\n\n==Result==\n{{Election box begin|title=By-election 2014: Clacton}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n  |votes      = 21,113\n  |percentage = 59.7\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Giles Watling]]\n  |votes      = 8,709\n  |percentage = 24.6\n  |change     = {{decrease}} 28.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Tim Young\n  |votes      = 3,957\n  |percentage = 11.2\n  |change     = {{decrease}} 13.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Chris Southall\n  |votes      = 688\n  |percentage = 1.9\n  |change     = {{increase}} 0.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Andrew Graham\n  |votes      = 483\n  |percentage = 1.4\n  |change     = {{decrease}} 11.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n  |party      = Independent\n  |candidate  = Bruce Sizer\n  |votes      = 205\n  |percentage = 0.6\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Official Monster Raving Loony Party\n  |candidate  =  [[Howling Laud Hope|Alan \"Howling Laud\" Hope]]\n  |votes      = 127\n  |percentage = 0.4\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n  |party      = Independent\n  |candidate  = [[Charlotte Rose]]\n  |votes      = 56\n  |percentage = 0.2\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n  |votes      = 12,404\n  |percentage = 35.1\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  |votes      = 35,338\n  |percentage = 51\n  |change     = \n}} \n{{Election box gain with party link\n |winner     = UK Independence Party\n |loser      = Conservative Party (UK)\n |swing      = {{increase}} 44.1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nThe election produced a number of [[United Kingdom by-election records|statistical records]], partly because of the unusual situation in which an incumbent MP with a large majority for one party has resigned and then stood for re-election on behalf of a new party for which support was in any case on a strongly rising trend. The 59.7% increase in the percentage vote achieved by UKIP since the previous general election (when they did not field a candidate) is the greatest ever in British parliamentary elections, although the percentage swing remains 0.1% less than the record 44.2% swing to the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] at the [[1983 Bermondsey by-election]].  The 28.4% reduction in Conservative votes is the 16th worst for any party since the Second World War, while the 1.4% of the vote achieved by the Liberal Democrats was, at the time, the third smallest vote ever obtained by a major party, and the worst since [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite interview |last=Curtice |first=John |subject-link=John Curtice |interviewer=[[Andrew Neil]] |title=Clacton by-election: Statistics of Douglas Carswell's win |type=Video |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29563847 |publisher=BBC News |date=10 October 2014 |access-date = 22 April 2014}}</ref> Since then, however, the Liberal Democrats received an even smaller proportion of the vote at the [[2014 Rochester and Strood by-election|Rochester and Strood by-election]] later in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rochester-byelection-lib-dems-blame-tactical-voting-for-partys-worst-ever-result-9876694.html |title=Rochester by-election: Lib Dems blame tactical voting for party\u2019s worst ever result |last=McSmith |first=Andy |work=The Independent |date=21 November 2014  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221093022/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rochester-byelection-lib-dems-blame-tactical-voting-for-partys-worst-ever-result-9876694.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 December 2014 |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Previous result==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|General election 2010]]: Clacton<ref name=2010result>{{cite news |title=Clacton |first= |last= |newspaper=[[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2010 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b14.stm }}</ref>}}\n\nUKIP did not stand a candidate against Douglas Carswell in 2010, citing his Eurosceptic views.\n\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n|party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Douglas Carswell]]\n|votes      = 22,867\n|percentage = 53.0\n|change     = {{increase}} 8.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Ivan Henderson]]\n|votes      = 10,799\n|percentage = 25.0\n|change     = {{decrease}} 10.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n|candidate  = Michael Green\n|votes      = 5,577\n|percentage = 12.9\n|change     = {{decrease}} 0.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = British National Party\n|candidate  = Jim Taylor\n|votes      = 1,975\n|percentage = 4.6\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n|party      = Tendring First\n|candidate  = Terry Allen\n|votes      = 1,078\n|percentage = 2.5\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n|candidate  = Chris Southall\n|votes      = 535\n|percentage = 1.2\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party      = Independent (politician)\n|candidate  = Chris Humphrey\n|votes      = 292\n|percentage = 0.7\n|change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n|votes      = 12,068\n|percentage = 28.0\n|change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n|votes      = 43,123\n|percentage = 64.2\n|change     = {{increase}} 1.6\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n|winn